Lat. In the civil and common law. Sufficient; competent; fit or
proper; responsible; unimpeachable. Jdoneus homo, a responsible or solvent person;
a good and lawful man. Sufficient; adequate; satisfactory. IJIdonea cautio, sufiicient security.

Public disgrace; infamy;
reproach; dishonor. Ignominy is the opposite of esteem. Wolff, § 145. See Brown
v. Kingsley, 38 Iowa, 220.

The condition before
the law, or the social status, of a bastard;
the state or condition of one whose parents

- were not intermarried at the time of his

birth. Miller vy. Miller, 18 Hun (N. Y.) 500;
Brown v. Belmarde, 8 Kan. 52.

Unilettered: ignorant;
unlearned. Generally used of one who cannot read and write. See In re Succession of
Carroll, 28 La. Ann. 888.

Iat. In the civil law. Expenses; outlays. Mackeld. Rom. Law, § 168;
Calvin. Divided into necessary, (necessarie,) useful, (utiles,) and tasteful or ornamental, (voluptuarie.) Dig. 50, 16, 79. See

Id. 25, 1.:

Pressing solicitation;
urgent request; application for a claim or
favor which is urged with troublesome frequency or pertinacity. Webster.

To arouse; stir up; instigate;
set in motion; as, to "incite" a riot. Also,
generally, in criminal law to instigate, persuade, or move another to commit a crime;
in this sense nearly synonymous with "abet."
See Long v. State, 23 Neb. 33, 36 N. W. 310.

Within six years.
Used in the Latin form of the plea of the
statute of limitations. |;

In old records. A nook or corner of a.common or fallow field, inclosed and
cultivated. Kennett, Par. Antig. 297, 298;
Cowell.

In old records. An inditch;
an interior ditch; one made within another,
for greater security. Spelman.

Meaning; will; purpose;
design. "The intention of the testator, to
be collected from the whole will, is to govern, provided it be not unlawful or inconsistent with the rules of law." 4 Kent, Comm.

One who is under pledge;
one who has had sureties or pledges given
for him. Spelman.

L. Lat. An enrolling;
a record.

Is QUI COGNOSCIT. Lat. The cognizor in a fine. Js cui cognoscitur, the cognizee.

In perpetual testimony of a matter;

for the purpose of declaring and settling a
thing forever. 1 Bl. Comm. 86.
